00:34:02.200 --> 00:34:13.200
[Amit Varma]: Vivek, before the break in the first half of the show, we spoke about the jobs crisis and you demystified a lot of the data thrown at us by Mr. Panagaria and Mr. Kumar.

00:34:13.200 --> 00:34:16.200
[Amit Varma]: What's the next subject you want to tackle?

00:34:16.200 --> 00:34:27.200
[Guest]: So, you know, there's this whole hangama happening around how the government is collecting more taxes after demonetization.

00:34:27.200 --> 00:34:37.200
[Guest]: And it's a very funny thing because, you know, obviously, as the economy grows, any government would collect more taxes.

00:34:37.200 --> 00:34:47.200
[Guest]: So what you need to look at are not direct taxes collected in the absolute sense of the term, but direct taxes collected as a proportion of the size of the economy.

00:34:47.200 --> 00:34:54.200
[Guest]: So the proportion, the size of the economy is essentially the gross domestic product or the GDP number.

00:34:54.200 --> 00:35:05.200
[Guest]: Now, so in 2017-18, the government of India, the direct tax collection was 5.94% of the GDP.

00:35:05.200 --> 00:35:13.200
[Guest]: Now, this was more than the taxes collected in 2016-17, which were at 5.6%.

00:35:13.200 --> 00:35:21.200
[Guest]: Now, before the Modi government came to power in 2013-14, the direct taxes to GDP ratio was 5.62%.

00:35:21.200 --> 00:35:25.200
[Guest]: And the collection over the next three years was lower than this number.

00:35:25.200 --> 00:35:31.200
[Guest]: In 2017-18, it improved to 5.94% of the GDP, which was a jump of around 34 basis points.

00:35:31.200 --> 00:35:39.200
[Guest]: So the moment you deflate the direct taxes number with the GDP number, you suddenly realize that the jump has not been as huge as claimed.

00:35:39.200 --> 00:35:44.200
[Guest]: I mean, if you look at in absolute terms, direct taxes have gone up by around 17-18%.

00:35:44.200 --> 00:35:49.200
[Guest]: There has also been increase in what the government calls the tax base.

00:35:49.200 --> 00:35:53.200
[Guest]: So this is essentially people who are filing returns.

00:35:53.200 --> 00:36:00.200
[Guest]: But then, as you know, we've discussed in the past, filing returns and paying taxes are two very different things.

00:36:00.200 --> 00:36:06.200
[Guest]: So when you file returns and don't pay taxes, the government does not benefit, your chartered accountant benefits.

00:36:06.200 --> 00:36:15.200
[Guest]: So even though the tax base is going up, it has not led to a proportionate increase in tax collections.

00:36:15.200 --> 00:36:20.200
[Guest]: So the argument offered here again is that, okay, you know, right now, these people are not paying.

00:36:20.200 --> 00:36:23.200
[Guest]: But in the years to come, as their income goes up, they'll start to pay.

00:36:23.200 --> 00:36:30.200
[Guest]: Now the problem with that argument is that in the years to come, as their income goes up and as the inflation goes up,

00:36:30.200 --> 00:36:34.200
[Guest]: the minimum exemption limit will also have to go up.

00:36:34.200 --> 00:36:39.200
[Guest]: I mean, it's but natural. That's how, you know, it's always been the case.

00:36:39.200 --> 00:36:42.200
[Guest]: And it's the right thing to do as well.

00:36:42.200 --> 00:36:54.200
[Guest]: The other thing that people don't talk about is that in 2007-08 and 2008-09, the direct taxes to GDP ratio was 6.3% and 5.93% respectively,

00:36:54.200 --> 00:37:01.200
[Guest]: which is, you know, one number is greater than the direct taxes collection in the last year and one number is almost similar.

00:37:01.200 --> 00:37:03.200
[Guest]: Now what happened back then?

00:37:03.200 --> 00:37:08.200
[Guest]: What had happened back then was that, you know, the stock market was rallying

00:37:08.200 --> 00:37:17.200
[Guest]: and obviously the government ended up collecting a lot of tax from the stock market in the form of securities transaction tax and in the form of short-term capital gains.

00:37:17.200 --> 00:37:22.200
[Guest]: My contention is that a similar thing could have happened in 2017-18 as well.

00:37:22.200 --> 00:37:23.200
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:37:23.200 --> 00:37:30.200
[Guest]: Right. I mean, the data for, you know, STT and short-term capital gains is not available in public domain.

00:37:30.200 --> 00:37:39.200
[Guest]: So if it was available in public domain, we could have sort of figured out as to, you know, how much tax is coming from STT and short-term capital gain

00:37:39.200 --> 00:37:44.200
[Guest]: and then sort of arrived at the, you know, whether demonetization has had an impact or not.

00:37:44.200 --> 00:37:49.200
[Guest]: What has also happened is that, you know, refunds have been delayed.

00:37:49.200 --> 00:37:55.200
[Guest]: So if, you know, the moment you delay refunds, your collection, the net direct tax number also goes up.

00:37:55.200 --> 00:38:04.200
[Guest]: So once you factor in all these things, you realize that, you know, again, it's a very strong case of optics management.

00:38:04.200 --> 00:38:11.200
[Amit Varma]: And also besides the refunds being delayed, one thing that you mentioned in your piece was that companies were asked to deposit TDS early.

00:38:11.200 --> 00:38:15.200
[Guest]: Yes, that was also a report in the Economic Times.

00:38:15.200 --> 00:38:20.200
[Guest]: And that also, so they were doing these various jogas to kind of get taxes up in the short term.

00:38:20.200 --> 00:38:25.200
[Guest]: Essentially to bump up the DTC number.

00:38:25.200 --> 00:38:31.200
[Amit Varma]: And what I'd say is the issue here that you're talking about is whether they were accurate with the claim or not.

00:38:31.200 --> 00:38:38.200
[Amit Varma]: The issue is not necessarily whether direct taxes going up are desirable or not, because it's irrelevant.

00:38:38.200 --> 00:38:42.200
[Guest]: In the context of our discussion, it's completely irrelevant.

00:38:42.200 --> 00:38:47.200
[Amit Varma]: We're just discussing that, okay, are they being truthful with whatever their claims are?

00:38:47.200 --> 00:38:56.200
[Amit Varma]: And if they are claiming X, did they do any short term jogas like being slow on giving refunds or making companies deposit TDS early to inflate the numbers?

00:38:56.200 --> 00:39:00.200
[Amit Varma]: So that the optics management, as you put it, works well.

00:39:00.200 --> 00:39:02.200
[Amit Varma]: Yes, precisely the point.

00:39:02.200 --> 00:39:05.200
[Amit Varma]: So this is about direct tax data.

00:39:05.200 --> 00:39:14.200
[Amit Varma]: You know, another very insightful piece you wrote in Business Standard, if I'm not mistaken, is about another, I don't know whether one would call it dishonesty,

00:39:14.200 --> 00:39:20.200
[Amit Varma]: but the way they manage the optics of the budget and in particular, the subsidies time bomb.

00:39:20.200 --> 00:39:27.200
[Guest]: Yes, so this is something that, and you cannot just blame the Modi government, it started with Mr. P Chidambaram.

00:39:27.200 --> 00:39:36.200
[Guest]: And so essentially, you know, you need to understand the fact that the government accounting works on cash systems,

00:39:36.200 --> 00:39:41.200
[Guest]: which basically means that revenue is accounted for when the money comes in.

00:39:41.200 --> 00:39:45.200
[Guest]: And, you know, expenditure is accounted for when the money goes out.

00:39:45.200 --> 00:39:55.200
[Guest]: Typically, in case, when companies account, that is based on the accrual system, wherein, if a sale is made, you know, it is booked as revenue,

00:39:55.200 --> 00:40:02.200
[Guest]: irrespective of the fact whether, you know, the customer, whoever the thing has been sold to has paid for it or not.

00:40:02.200 --> 00:40:04.200
[Guest]: Okay, that is a basic difference.

00:40:04.200 --> 00:40:11.200
[Guest]: So essentially, what the governments tend to do is they tend to postpone the payment of subsidies.

00:40:11.200 --> 00:40:18.200
[Guest]: So there are largely three kinds of subsidies, food, fertilizer, and petroleum.

00:40:18.200 --> 00:40:23.200
[Amit Varma]: And these are made by these government agencies like the Food Corporation of India, and they have to take the money from the government.

00:40:23.200 --> 00:40:31.200
[Guest]: So basically, what happens is, so let's say, you know, the Food Corporation of India buys rice and wheat primarily from farmers,

00:40:31.200 --> 00:40:37.200
[Guest]: and they pay them an X rate, 14 rupees a kg, 15 rupees a kg, I don't remember the exact number, but somewhere along those lines.

00:40:37.200 --> 00:40:45.200
[Guest]: And then they sell that rice and wheat to the public distribution system at a price of 2 to 3 rupees a kg.

00:40:45.200 --> 00:40:49.200
[Guest]: And then there is also the cost of moving that grain around.

00:40:49.200 --> 00:40:57.200
[Guest]: So the government has to compensate the Food Corporation of India for that difference.

00:40:57.200 --> 00:41:02.200
[Guest]: Now, what it tends to do is that the government does not pay on time.

00:41:02.200 --> 00:41:10.200
[Guest]: So let's say, you know, some amount of subsidy was due in 2017-18, it wouldn't have been paid in 17-18, it will be paid in 18-19.

00:41:10.200 --> 00:41:19.200
[Guest]: So the moment they don't pay it in 17-18, they don't have to account for it as an expenditure, simply because it's a cash accounting system.

00:41:19.200 --> 00:41:21.200
[Amit Varma]: Sir, I'll ask a layman question, clarify this.

00:41:21.200 --> 00:41:26.200
[Amit Varma]: If this was a private company, the moment that even if they didn't pay, that expenditure would still be on the books?

00:41:26.200 --> 00:41:29.200
[Guest]: It would still be on the books because it's been incurred.

00:41:29.200 --> 00:41:31.200
[Amit Varma]: But in case of the government, it's not on the books?

00:41:31.200 --> 00:41:34.200
[Amit Varma]: No, not on the books because the government is not incurring the expenditure itself.

00:41:34.200 --> 00:41:38.200
[Guest]: There is an agency which incurs the expenditure.

00:41:38.200 --> 00:41:40.200
[Guest]: So I'll give you some numbers.

00:41:40.200 --> 00:41:46.200
[Guest]: So as of 2017-18, and this is data from the Comptroller and Auditor General,

00:41:46.200 --> 00:41:57.200
[Guest]: the total subsidies outstanding were 2,19,774 crore. Of this, FCI was owed 2,04,376 crore.

00:41:57.200 --> 00:42:02.200
[Guest]: Now what happens is the natural question that one may ask now is that how does FCI function?

00:42:02.200 --> 00:42:09.200
[Guest]: If, you know, such a huge amount of money is not paid to an organization, I mean, how does it continue to function?

00:42:09.200 --> 00:42:18.200
[Guest]: So FCI essentially continues to function because it keeps borrowing and banks are happy to lend to FCI because FCI is basically the government.

00:42:18.200 --> 00:42:28.200
[Guest]: So typically what happens is that when FCI borrows, it has to pay interest on that borrowing.

00:42:28.200 --> 00:42:33.200
[Guest]: So that interest also gets added on to the subsidy burden.

00:42:33.200 --> 00:42:37.200
[Amit Varma]: And listeners should know that all of you and me and Vivek are paying this interest.

00:42:37.200 --> 00:42:44.200
[Guest]: Of course, I mean, because in some form or the other, I mean, we are paying for it in the form of high petrol and diesel prices for one.

00:42:44.200 --> 00:42:54.200
[Guest]: So essentially, you know, an estimate made by the CAG suggests that between 2011 and 2016,

00:42:54.200 --> 00:43:04.200
[Guest]: the Food Corporation of India paid an interest of more than 35,000 crore on all the money they had borrowed because the government had not paid them on time.

00:43:04.200 --> 00:43:10.200
[Amit Varma]: And the government is not paying them on time. So it can do this accounting trick of saying that, hey, we've kept the fiscal deficit under control.

00:43:10.200 --> 00:43:11.200
[Amit Varma]: We're not spending so much.

00:43:11.200 --> 00:43:17.200
[Guest]: So this basically started during the Chidambaram era. And, you know, back then, I think the number was around 100,000 crore.

00:43:17.200 --> 00:43:25.200
[Guest]: And over the last four years, it sort of doubled and reached around 2,20,000 crores.

00:43:25.200 --> 00:43:30.200
[Guest]: And you described this as a subsidies time bomb. Is it going to explode? What's going to happen?

00:43:30.200 --> 00:43:34.200
[Guest]: Yeah, see, it'll not. I mean, it's a time bomb, yes, but the thing with…

00:43:34.200 --> 00:43:35.200
[Amit Varma]: Every year, they'll kick it down the road.

00:43:35.200 --> 00:43:39.200
[Guest]: Yeah, so the government, essentially, the government fiscal deficit is basically a Ponzi scheme, right?

00:43:39.200 --> 00:43:40.200
[Guest]: Right.

00:43:40.200 --> 00:43:47.200
[Guest]: You know, it keeps running because the government issues bonds and, you know, new set of investors keeps coming in. So…

00:43:47.200 --> 00:43:51.200
[Amit Varma]: In fact, there was a great demand on Twitter that I ask you about Ponzi schemes.

00:43:51.200 --> 00:43:53.200
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, but that is a separate…

00:43:53.200 --> 00:43:54.200
[Amit Varma]: That's a separate episode.

00:43:54.200 --> 00:44:00.200
[Guest]: Episode, and I haven't written on Ponzi schemes for a while, so I'll have to read up and…

00:44:00.200 --> 00:44:06.200
[Amit Varma]: Though he has written a book, which you must read, called India's Big Government, and what is that, if not a Ponzi scheme?

00:44:06.200 --> 00:44:07.200
[Guest]: Yeah, so…

00:44:07.200 --> 00:44:08.200
[Guest]: In many ways.

00:44:08.200 --> 00:44:19.200
[Guest]: Yes, so I guess, yeah, that sort of… because, you know, the government at the end of the day is a Ponzi scheme, so they can continue.

00:44:19.200 --> 00:44:32.200
[Guest]: And, I mean, so there are other ways. I mean, you look at the fact that the amount of money, you know, I think 20-21% of the deposits that the banks collect have to compulsorily be invested in government securities.

00:44:32.200 --> 00:44:33.200
[Guest]: Wow.

00:44:33.200 --> 00:44:40.200
[Guest]: Then you have the insurance companies, they have to sort of compulsorily invest money in government securities.

00:44:40.200 --> 00:44:49.200
[Guest]: So the government in its own way has ensured that, you know, the demand for the debt that it issues continues.

00:44:49.200 --> 00:44:58.200
[Guest]: I mean, the term that economists use for it in the Western world is financial repression.

00:44:58.200 --> 00:45:04.200
[Guest]: And in India, because we are so used to the idea of financing the government, the citizens, that we don't even realize it.

00:45:04.200 --> 00:45:16.200
[Amit Varma]: This is another fascinating subject and all the listeners of this show who are fans of Vivek Kaul, I'd urge you to go to Twitter, find him at Kaul underscore Vivek and bombard the guy insisting that he write these two books.

00:45:16.200 --> 00:45:22.200
[Amit Varma]: One on how government is a Ponzi scheme and two on how government uses data.

00:45:22.200 --> 00:45:30.200
[Amit Varma]: Moving on now to general questions, you know, you are an experienced financial journalist and you have an eye for numbers and you are trained to figure all this stuff out.

00:45:30.200 --> 00:45:32.200
[Guest]: I am not really trained.

00:45:32.200 --> 00:45:35.200
[Guest]: But you're sort of self-taught. You're an autodidact.

00:45:35.200 --> 00:45:37.200
[Amit Varma]: Baba. Whatever that means.

00:45:37.200 --> 00:45:41.200
[Amit Varma]: You're an autodidact data detective.

00:45:41.200 --> 00:45:44.200
[Guest]: Autodidact data detective. A.D.

00:45:44.200 --> 00:45:46.200
[Amit Varma]: There's a lot of D in there.

00:45:46.200 --> 00:45:51.200
[Amit Varma]: It sounds like one of those syndromes, you know, which you don't know of.

00:45:51.200 --> 00:45:58.200
[Amit Varma]: But back to my question, what is a concerned citizen to do to keep a government accountable as far as the truth is concerned?

00:45:58.200 --> 00:46:07.200
[Guest]: It's very tricky, you know, in the, you know, daily life living, you know, making an earning and, you know, getting to office and coming back.

00:46:07.200 --> 00:46:16.200
[Guest]: It's very difficult. So I guess the only thing you can do is to try and read a wide variety of people.

00:46:16.200 --> 00:46:30.200
[Guest]: Given, I mean, and to be, you know, not trust everything that arrives on WhatsApp and, you know, just follow a few, you know, people on the social media and try reading them out.

00:46:30.200 --> 00:46:38.200
[Guest]: I mean, I don't think there is. See, unless people sort of go looking for knowledge and try understanding things, it's not going to happen.

00:46:38.200 --> 00:46:47.200
[Guest]: And you cannot blame them, given the fact that life is difficult, there is only so much time, there are pressures from the family, you know, there are bosses sitting on the head.

00:46:47.200 --> 00:46:54.200
[Guest]: Everyone's not as lucky as, you know, I am to, you know, who gets the time and gets paid to do all this.

00:46:54.200 --> 00:47:04.200
[Amit Varma]: And I think what I clarify, and I'm sure you'll agree with me, and as Plato's quote, in fact, pointed out, is that this is something that is embedded in human nature and in the way governments function.

00:47:04.200 --> 00:47:08.200
[Amit Varma]: So, this is not particularly about this specific government.

00:47:08.200 --> 00:47:14.200
[Guest]: Right, I mean, we tend to like stories. So, I'll give you a very interesting example, I mean, something that happened today.

00:47:14.200 --> 00:47:18.200
[Guest]: So, A.B. De Villiers retired yesterday.

00:47:18.200 --> 00:47:19.200
[Guest]: Very.

00:47:19.200 --> 00:47:20.200
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, out of the blue.

00:47:20.200 --> 00:47:21.200
[Amit Varma]: Very sad for me.

00:47:21.200 --> 00:47:23.200
[Guest]: Out of the blue. Now, that's a different thing.

00:47:23.200 --> 00:47:35.200
[Guest]: So, now suddenly you have this WhatsApp forward going around, which says that, you know, De Villiers was a champion hockey player, a champion tennis player, a champion rugby player, champion golf player at the school level.

00:47:35.200 --> 00:47:42.200
[Guest]: Now, it's very difficult to sort of believe that one guy could have been, you know, good at so many sports, right.

00:47:42.200 --> 00:47:49.200
[Guest]: And so, I just sort of googled and I realized that this is some fake news, which has been going around for a while now.

00:47:49.200 --> 00:47:53.200
[Guest]: And De Villiers has clarified that all this is wrong.

00:47:53.200 --> 00:47:59.200
[Guest]: And he said that the only sports that he played for a year was hockey in his school or college or something like that.

00:47:59.200 --> 00:48:08.200
[Guest]: Now, so, one guy who had sent it to me and I told him this and his immediate response was,

00:48:08.200 --> 00:48:19.200
[Amit Varma]: what happened, at least he looks good when he reads. So, it's inspiring. My response would have been, Vivek, you break the government's laws, let it be. I feel like you just told me Santa Claus doesn't exist.

00:48:19.200 --> 00:48:27.200
[Guest]: No, I mean, if you look at A.B. De Villiers, I mean, he's done enough on the cricket field itself to be categorized as a legend.

00:48:27.200 --> 00:48:29.200
[Amit Varma]: But we are a storytelling species.

00:48:29.200 --> 00:48:31.200
[Guest]: Yes, so people love this, you know, here's this guy.

00:48:31.200 --> 00:48:37.200
[Guest]: So, in fact, if you remember correctly, there used to be the same sort of stories going around for John T. Rhodes also.

00:48:37.200 --> 00:48:41.200
[Guest]: But John T. Rhodes apparently was a great hockey player.

00:48:41.200 --> 00:48:51.200
[Guest]: He would have easily made it into the South African hockey team as a center forward if he had not chosen to sort of play cricket.

00:48:51.200 --> 00:48:55.200
[Guest]: But cricket was, you know, paid, hockey did not.

00:48:55.200 --> 00:49:01.200
[Guest]: No, I think hockey in South Africa, when he used to be around, was played at an amateur level.

00:49:01.200 --> 00:49:04.200
[Guest]: And thank goodness for that, because so many hours of pleasure.

00:49:04.200 --> 00:49:08.200
[Guest]: So, you know, you can understand one guy being good at two sports.

00:49:08.200 --> 00:49:11.200
[Guest]: One guy can be good at some six, seven different sports.

00:49:11.200 --> 00:49:16.200
[Amit Varma]: No, but apparently Bal Narendra, when he was a young lad, was excellent at a lot of sports.

00:49:16.200 --> 00:49:18.200
[Amit Varma]: Now we are getting into tricky territory.

